In message <3ulbrj$4tb@nntp.crl.com> - vhealey@crl.com (Vic Healey) writes:
:>VFAT is far superior to HPFS when you think about it in real world use
:>
:>  * 32 bit VFAT file system vs old 16 bit HPFS in WARP

The disk structure of HPFS is 16-bit, not the code.  What difference does it
make to have a 32-bit structure on the disk?  The bit number is the size of
the value that points to a cluster.
12 bits can have up to 4096 clusters (this is floppy drives).
16 bits can have up to 65536 clusters (this is FAT and HPFS).
32 bits can have 4.2e9 clusters (the is VFAT).

Let me make it clear, the VFAT allocation table will take up twice as much
space as FAT.


:>  * 32 bit Vcache makes for fast fast access in W95

OS/2 does 32-bit disk access.

:>  * old dos old win can  still read the files even when W95 or
:>NT isn't loaded
:>  * HPFS files can only be read if OS/2 is running. When OS/2 is
:>boggered up by a system crash and will not even reboot you are locked
:>out of your files until you repair the system. You could toataly trash
:>W95 and still get to your disk data by booting old dos.

There are DOS programs (public domain, in fact) that access HPFS from DOS
(some even can write to HPFS).

:>  * Dos 6.22, W95 and NT can use VFAT without fear of damaging the disk
:>structure, OS/2 may cause problems since it dosn't understand VFAT yet

Do you mean that a defrag program written for DOS will work correctly on
VFAT?  I doubt that.

:>  * Super long file names mean that you can avoid having to comment file
:>names in as seperate file like 4Dos does.

Who doesn't have long files names?  Some of us have been using them for a
long time.

:>  * A simple defrag utiltiy that comes with W95 can check and optimise
:>VFAT in the background if needed to keep VFAT operating at full speed

HPFS resists fragmentation.  When a file is written, it is written
unfragmented.  Any idiot can write a program to pick-up ever file on the
drive and re-write it.  Doesn't take Peter Norton.

:>  * VFAT dosn't suffer from the incredible system slow down found when a
:>HPFS drive becomes 90% full.

Never heard of this, give me proof.  Explain...

:>All those who scornfully post that VFAT is a cludge should be asked
:>why the vaunted  HPFS falls short in so many real world areas as far
:>as the user is concerned.

How does HPFS fail at everyday tasks?  Explain your reasons!
Here is my idea of a real-world task... searching the hard drive for files.
OS/2 searches my 411 meg HPFS drive in 6 seconds, everytime, whether i'm
looking for wildcards or a single file.

I think that is good.

:>OS/2-> only half an PC OS the Windows 95 compatible part is missing

