In message <3ulm00$agk@mars.earthlink.net> - rhartma@earthlink.net writes:
:>:>FAT has a maximum of 65K clusters that it can use. That means you start getting
:>pretty big in the cluster department when 1G drives are getting cheap! Clusters on
:>a 1G drive are 16K-32K. Clusters on a 4G drive are 64K. That means the smallest
:>space a file can occupy is 1 cluster. Ergo, if you have 64K clusters, AUTOEXEC.BAT
:>and CONFIG.SYS will occupy 1 cluster each. Thats 64K. The average loss per any
:>file on your disk will be 1/2 cluster. If a file were to be 65K, then it would have to
:>occupy 2 clusters. On a 1G drive, 200M of space can be wasted on it easily by this
:>clunky use of clusters. It's worse on afore mentioned 2G drive.

This may not be true.  Unless I am mistaken, VFAT has a 32-bit structure
(that is what all the fuse is about, right?).  In that case, it would use
2e31 clusters.  This would creatly reduce the size of clusters on the hard
disk while doubling the size of the FAT (no big deal, though).

Fact it, a 16-bit file structure is no slower than a 32-bit one.  The DESIGN
is the important thing.  HPFS is fast by design.


